48. Carinae z Virg. Aen. 8. 361 ‘lautis . . . Carinis3' a fashionable quarter where Philippus may be supposed to have had a house. It was on the Mons Op- pius, the southern spur of the Esquiline, which runs out towards the Arch of Titus. The Sacra Via commenced in the Carinae, and ran through the Forum.

Itis pointed out that the two names together implied that he was a freedman, Volteius being a Roman gentile name, the name of his ‘patronus,’ Menas, a Greek name, con- tracted from Menodorus. Bishop Lightfoot, in notes on Coloss. 4. 12, 14, 15, has collected a large number of such contracted names.

56. praeconem, an auctioneer, as we see from v. 65. Cp. A. P. 419 ‘praeco ad merces qui turbam cogit emendas.’
